55":"circa 1455","1483":"1483","about 1450":"circa 1450","1526":"1526","Europe":"Europa","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"en":{"about 1425–after 1459":"about 1425–after 1459","1425–1459":"1425–1459","1425–1483":"1425–1483","1455–1526":"1455–1526","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1459":"1459","before 1425":"before 1425","1425":"1425","after 1459":"after 1459","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","about 1425":"about 1425","about 1455":"about 1455","1483":"1483","about 1450":"about 1450","1526":"1526","Europe":"Europe","Essex, England":"Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Knollys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Knowles  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Knowles","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>knol(le)</i> ‘knoll, hilltop’ (Old English <i>cnoll</i>) or from any of the many places (some lost) named with this word, for example Knowle (Devon, Dorset, Lancashire, Somerset, Warwickshire, and Yorkshire) and Knole (Kent, Sussex).","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tnúthghail</b> (see   Newell  ).","English: variant of   Noel  , often, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Knollys was born about 1425, in Europe as the daughter of Robert Knollys and Elizabeth Seman. She married Robert Barrett about 1450. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1459."},"et":{"about 1425–after 1459":"umbes 1425–pärast 1459","1425–1459":"1425–1459","1425–1483":"1425–1483","1455–1526":"1455–1526","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1459":"1459","before 1425":"e